t they had about her dark blood, hmmm...&quot;.<br>
<br>
     Giltaav's mind flashed back to the first encounter he'd had with the half elf.  He had run from the Nexus, through the airless space called The Grey, and into the Scarlet Desert to join some companions who were hunting the Blood Tribe.  The Wave Caller had introduced him to a prospective member of the Elven Elite, none other than Ivri.  After a few battles with the tribe, the group recieved a note from Aryllyian, telling the group to come to the Twilight Sea to give Ivri a formal invitation to the guild, which she accepted.  No sooner had the group returned to the Blood Tribe cave than they were assaulted by reinforcements the tribe had called in, and a viscious bloody battle ensued.  With only one true healer in the group, Firinn was the only one who could keep the group alive through the battle, knowing this, the Tribe sent two of their best warriors to slay the Bear.  Giltaav had watched in horror as the tribe warriors made quick work of the Bear, only to see Ivri turn from the warrior she was currently engaged with, and lay a healing hand on the Bear, saving his life, but sacrificing herself to the fury of the warriors.  The battle was won, but in the aftermath, Ivri's body was found lifeless under one of the Tribe warriors.  &quot;A fine way to start her membership in the guild&quot; he thought &quot;we go and get her killed&quot;.  The Wave Caller summoned her soul back to her body however, and the battles continued without further incidents.<br>
<br>
     His mind jumping back to the present, Giltaav scrounged up some eggs and ham and made breakfast.  He thought to himself &quot;Hmm... maybe Firinn should be less concerned about the words Ivri had spoken in anger, and should think about her actions when things came down to the line... no Tier'Dal would have sacrificed herself in battle to save the life of another... more likely she would have left the moment things went bad&quot;.  Before leaving, Giltaav scooped up the pieces of the note and snuck towards Firinn's sleeping quarters.  The door being locked, Giltaav sighed and quietly shoved the torn parchment under the door.  That done, he grabbed his gear and left the hall to find what adventure this day had in store. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#AB8C5B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/unaminumt.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Naminu MT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Power User</span><br>  Posts: 255<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(10/18/02 5:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=79.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A new day begins</span><hr size=1>    It had been a lovely slow morning. Instead of chasing after her usual companions Naminu had stayed home in the guild hall to bake. The typically neat elf had flour dusted across her simple green dress and hands. It's funny she mused I never feel better than when I am helping my guildmates whether it's with a sword in my hand or a mixing spoon. In the oven there were fish rolls baking to a lovely brown and pies already cooling on the window sill. Naminu had giggled to herself as she set out the pies, the thought had ocured to her that the Elite were very lucky there were no lurking gnomes about.<br>
<br>
   Waiting for her bread to rise a second time she took a kettle off of the shelf to make some tea. It was a cool breezy day outside and while the kitchen was warm she thought the drink would sooth her. Just as she was headed to the pantry to select the tea she heard a noise bump down the hall. She smiled to herself, it must be Ivri. So far she was the only elf in the area that hadn't been through the kitchen. The smile faded as she remebered the half conversation she had with Giltaav as he had left this morning. Ivri was fighting a battle with a monster that could not be slayed with a sword. Naminu brushed off her skirt and straightened her back. It was her duty to help.. then she laughed at herself .. duty? honor perhaps pleasure more like. She turned back to the kitchen.<br>
<br>
   A few minutes later she was tapping on the door of Ivri's room. &quot;Go away,&quot; came the mumble from under the door. Not one to be easily turned away Naminu tapped again. Silence greeted her. &quot;I know you are awake and I'm coming in on the count of three,&quot; Naminu said smiling to herself &quot;One orc centurian, two orc centurian, three orc centurian&quot; and with that she opened the door. Ivri still had her legs curled up under the blanket but she was sitting up and looked mildy awake. &quot;Hmmmm I expected you to be out of bed already, I heard thumping earlier,&quot; the high elf said holding out a steaming mug. &quot;Oh that,&quot; Ivri said as she took the mug &quot;I think I accidentally kicked my gauntlets off the bed. Not all my armor made it into that pile in the front room.&quot; She sniffed and looked into the mug she had been handed. &quot;What's this?&quot;<br>
&quot;Tea,&quot; came the reply &quot;It should help soothe your sore muscles.&quot; Ivri took a tentative sip, looked up smiled, then took a longer drink. &quot;It's good but I've not had anything like it before, what's in it?&quot; Naminu walked over and sat at the foot of the bed before she replied, &quot;The tea is made with only rain water and the bark of evergreen trees. Made from the love of Karana falling down on the earth and the love of Tunare growing up from the earth.&quot; Naminu paused and looked at the half-elf in front of her. &quot;You know, there are evergreen trees in Nektolus Forest and rain falls there as well. Good can come from unusual sources.&quot; Ivri looked at her with suprise but Naminu held up her hand for silence. &quot;I do not need to know the details because I know you. I have seen your noble acts. I have seen the steel in your eyes as you slay the evil undead and the joy as you share stories with your friends. These are the things that matter. Parentage  does not create the person... just look at Carthaz... just look at me...... I have perhaps said to much now but know that I stand with you no matter what comes.&quot; Naminu stood and began to leave the room, as she reached the door she turned back around and said, &quot;The bear is a hard headed beast and a smart one, he also has his pride. Maybe don't sharpen the stick before you poke him next time.&quot; and with those words still in the air she closed the door behind her. <br>
   <br>
    <p>Naminu, Calling Waves for 51 seasons<BR><BR><img src="http://web.bvub.com/~carthaz/namisig.jpg"></img></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#BA9F70><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=aryllyian>Aryllyian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Officer</span><br>  Posts: 1287<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(10/19/02 9:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=79.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A new day begins</span><hr size=1> Aryllyian strode into the Paladin's guild in Felwithe without even the slightest pretense of stopping for the guards.  By now, the younger squires had learned to judge Ary's mood and today was not the day to confront him.<br>
<br>
He removed his helm as he bounded the spiral stairs of the northern tower. Along the way, a host of scribes chased Aryllyian looking for signatures and approvals.  Ary reached the top of the stairs, slipped inside his office and slammed the heavy wooden door shut behind him.  The scribes stood for a moment with a questioning look, before turning away frustrated.<br>
<br>
&quot;Tis not the day for bureaucracy&quot; mumbled Aryllyian under his breath.<br>
<br>
Ary stood for a long moment, gazing out over the fertile orchards of Felwithe.  He was struck at the bounty that Tunare provided his people.  It had been a hard-fought but fortunate year.<br>
<br>
He stood in front of his desk and removed the rest of his armor, placing each piece on an ancient armor stand.  For Aryllyian removing his armor had become a ritual of cleansing, and he considered the ritual cathartic.<br>
<br>
When he was finished he sat at his desk and wrapped his burgundy cloak about him.  He paused for a moment, then began a letter:<br>
<br>
Wilwen Hood,<br>
<br>
Greetings! I am aware that your travels take you far from home, and into mortal danger, May Tunare keep you well.  The gentle lady Irislilly asks about you often, I am sure, when time permits, a letter would satisfy her curiosity...if it can be called that.<br>
<br>
To Business, My lord:<br>
<br>
The Western city of Qeynos, that wretched cauldron where all things breed without conscience, has caused me some manner of concern.   Being imbued by eternal friendship, our association within the Elite and the cause for good, I beg a favor.  I am inquiring as the the history of a being called Ivri, a half Human.  Whether this information is obtained through your personal cleverness or thru the network of likeminded associations, I care not.  It matters only to be that the information be accurate.<br>
<br>
Fare the well..and May Tunare bless,<br>
<br>
Aryllyian Wyndreaver<br>
<br>
<br>
______________<br>
&quot;Bard!&quot; Aryllyian screamed.  A bard approached at blinding speed.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have a message for Wilwen Hood, he can be found near that Temple in the Western Wastes.   If he is not there...check the brothels in Freeport or Grobb&quot; <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=aryllyian>Aryllyian</A> at: 10/19/02 7:58:59 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#AB8C5B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wilwenhoodmt>Wilwen Hood MT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Officer and Bat Lover!</span><br>  Posts: 246<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(11/12/02 3:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=79.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A rogue's saga begins</span><hr size=1> It was a dark night in Highpass, yet, the tavern seemed booming with vitality as light poured welcomingly through its ever-open doors.  A single voice could be heard coming from within the building.<br>
<br>
Inside, the patrons seemed oddly quite, their attentions all focused towards a black-clad figure, sitting at a table in the middle of the room, his flowing blonde hair glowing in the torchlight.  Sitting around him, watching him, listening to his every word were a group of young ladies; some of human descent, some of Elven blood, and even several of mixed heritage.  At the far end of the room, sat their husbands and would-be suitors, jealous of the one who had captured their lovers' hearts.  He was none other than Wilwen the Hood, having returned after a long absence, with stories of his many adventures.<br>
<br>
&quot;So there we were,&quot; the rogue continued, &quot;deep within the plane of disease.  We had stormed the castle, and, after single handedly defeating the Spider Guardian, I lead our force down towards the chamber of Grummus.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I thought you said you were asked to join the attack, now you say you were leading it?&quot;  A bearded northman shouted from across the room.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sir, and I use the term loosely, you did not let me finish,&quot; the rogue replied with a smirk, &quot;for you see, the great warrior leading the attack had become so stricken with fear, that he had sent word that a true hero was needed to take his place and lead the final push.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, Wilwen!&quot; cried the rogue's company as they huddled closer to him.  The northman returned to his seat, stroking his beard in defeat.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now, where was I?&quot; asked Wilwen, pulling a young elf close to his side.<br>
<br>
&quot;Y-you w-were just about to lead the final attack on Grummus s-sir,&quot; she replied nervously.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sir?&quot; he asked, taking her hand, and kissing it gently, &quot;please, call me Wilwen,&quot; he added, as she swooned.  &quot;Ah, yes,&quot; he continued, &quot;the attack on Grummus,&quot; Wilwen paused.  &quot;Well, you see, umm, when faced with great adversity, sometimes mighty fighters such as myself go into a -what is it called- ah, a blood rage!  Once the foul demon presented himself, my vision, it, umm, went dark, and when I awoke -err- could see again, I lay on the cold stone ground, soaked in blood.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Did you win?&quot; a young half-breed sitting next to him asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, umm...barkeep!&quot; Wilwen shouted abruptly, &quot;Another round of black wine for my 'companions' here!&quot;  A cheer went up from his female companions as their male friends glowered from across the room.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's getting late,&quot; the rogue yawned as he stretched, putting his arms around the elves that sat on either side of him. &quot;Think it's about time for bed?&quot; he asked his two companions as he stood up from the table, making his way towards the stairs with the two elves still in arm.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mr. Hood!&quot; cried an unfamiliar voice from the tavern threshold.  &quot;Wilwen Hood!&quot; it cried again.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're going to have to wait until morning for another story, young man,&quot; Wilwen replied as he began to climb the stairs towards his room.  &quot;I am quite tired, and have a pair of elves that I must be getting to bed,&quot; he added, smiling coyly.<br>
<br>
“I bring you a message from Lord Arryllyian; he assured me that it is urgent!” replied the young lad as he stepped towards the rogue.<br>
<br>
Wilwen turned, and could see that the young man indeed spoke the truth.  He was a messenger of the Elven Elite, and carried a note sealed with the official guild crest.<br>
<br>
“Pardon me, ladies,” the rogue smirked, “this must be some official business of the Elven Elite.  Have I told you that I am an officer of the guild?” he asked smiling, inciting an even greater sense of awe in his companions.<br>
<br>
Wilwen walked towards the messenger, taking the letter from his hand.  “They are probably sending me off on a dangerous mission again,” he said loudly.  Unsheathing Ragebringer, he used the point of the blade to break the seal.  “Probably the Plane of Hate or Temple of Veeshan” he trailed off as he began to read quietly to himself.  Suddenly, all mirth left his face.  “Qeynos,” he muttered to himself, “Ivri…could it be?” he asked himself, letting go of the two elves who now stood puzzled by his side.<br>
<br>
With a sudden sense of urgency, the rogue sheathed Ragebringer, snatched up his cloak, and, while fastening it around his neck, made his way towards the door.  “Bard,” he said at turning back from the door “I must seek the council of Stanos.  Travel to the eastern Karanas and seek out a ranger by the name of Tegyen.  You need not look hard, for he will surely find you before you can him.  Inform him that he must head to Qeynos, where he will get a room at the local inn.” The rogue explained, covering his golden locks with a dark hood as he turned once again for the door.<br>
<br>
“Shall I tell him anything else, milord?” asked the young lad, who had been carefully recording the rogue’s message.<br>
<br>
“Just tell him to travel to Qeynos and await my arrival.” The rogue replied as he turned one last time from the door.  “Tell him Wilwen-,” he added, pausing to look once more at the letter he had received, “Tell him his father needs him.” <br>
<br>
And with a dash as fast as a leaf caught in a strong wind, the black-clad rogue disappeared into the night, while the bard finished the note and made arrangements to spend the night at the tavern, for in the morning, he would seek out the ranger Tegyen with his urgent communicae.<br>
