<br>
Myrrer enters &quot;Top of the World&quot; with a smirk upon his face.  He saunters up to the bar next to another halfling.  &quot;My good herald the Shortling Syndicate has work tonight,&quot; he states in a hushed voice.<br>
<br>
The halfling smiles and pulls out quill, ink and parchment as Myrrer begins to dictate<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Dear Brother,<br>
The Shortling Syndicate is moving forward at the bidding of the mischeivous Bristlebane.  You must travel to Queynos and seek Renux.  Tell her that the Shortling Syndicate has devised a means for her to get back at Wilwen Hood.  Mr. Hood shall soon arrive in Queynos inquiring about the herritage of a Half-Human, Ivri.  His attempts to gather this information will utilize your fathers networks and therefore she alone can make this work.  <br>
Make Mr. Hood believe that the lineage of Ivri is Elvish and Human.  However, the Elvish nature is a mixture of Dark Elf and High Elf.  It seems that her father was the offspring of a drunken encounter between the High Elf, Ellail (brother to Aryllyian) and an unknown Dark Elf.  The child resembled his Dark Elf ancestory and was raised a Drow.  His subsequent relationship with a human resulted in to birth of this Ivri.  A tainted Half-Elf, with a direct bloodline to the Grand Moff himself.  Tell Renux, that this is her opportunity to make the rogue that denied her advances pay!  Once Aryllyian realizes Wilwen's folly, Wilwen will be disgraced.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
&quot;Seal the note with the Syndicate Seal and take it to Myrris in Rivervale.  He'll take it from there,&quot; chortled Myrrer.<br>
<br>
The scribe sealed the note and departed.<br>
<br>
Myrrer's thoughts were racing, &quot;Now to return to the Guildhall and watch the games play out.  I will finally get one on the pretentious Grand Moff and Prince of Thieves... oh yes, you Prince of Thieves, You.<br>
&quot;Ivri may even get a laugh at such an absurdity that Aryllyian and Wilwen takes to be fact.&quot;<br>
<br>
With the mischevious smirk permenantly afixed, Myrrer leaves for the journy home.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=myrrer>myrrer</A> at: 11/12/02 7:29:32 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#AB8C5B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ivri>Ivri</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(11/14/02 1:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=79.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Journey &quot;Home&quot;</span><hr size=1> Ivri groaned as the bright sun of Norrath hit her eyes that morning.  She rolled over and hid her face under her blanket.  “Gah, I’m getting too soft, I don’t ever remember the ground being this hard when I was here last,” she complained to herself.  “Here” was the plains of Northern Karana.  She had packed her meager belongings and set out a few days before, and even now, she was still unsure of her decision.  Was she truly going to accomplish anything by returning, or was she bringing more trouble into her life?  Karana knew she certainly didn’t need any more trouble.  She stared thoughtfully at the underside of her blanket as she remembered the conversation that had led to this decision.<br>
<br>
She had been up late that night, as usual, and had just entered the Guildhall to get some rest.  Rather unexpectedly, Firinn had been sitting in the corner of the dining area.  She assumed that perhaps the shaman could not sleep either, and so she decided that now was as good a time as any to try to be sociable.  She had gotten him to tell her a little about his childhood, and about his parents who, unfortunately, had been slain by frost giants a long time ago.  He told her about his wandering, and how he came to the Elven Elite, of the kindness of Eliani and Slaini and how they had taken him into their home.  She could tell that he obviously considered the Elite to be his family, and he cared for them very much.  <br>
“I see now why he is so very protective of them, and suspicious of me…I would be too, if I were him,” she thought to herself.  Just when she thought that perhaps he was beginning to accept her, everything went horridly wrong.<br>
<br>
“Don’t act like you don’t know of which I speak!” he stated hotly, staring her down.<br>
“I do not know what you mean, shaman, perhaps you should explain it to me, since you are so wise,” Ivri replied, her voice dripping with sarcasm.<br>
“Surely, paladin,” he countered, “You recall the ‘jest’ for which you demand an apology.”<br>
“Oh, I see,” she said, her voice rising, “Humor is not allowed, is it?  Even humor is now evil?”<br>
“Humor has limits, for it is always at someone’s expense, which is why you demand apology,” Firinn stated.  “I’m not entirely convinced you didn’t lead me down the path of that discussion in order to make yourself a martyr.”<br>
“A martyr?  I never intended that you insult me in such a manner!”  She scowled and stood up to leave the table.<br>
He said quietly to her back, “And your insults were less?”<br>
She slowly turned around, her gaze dropping to her boots.  “I did take it…a bit too far, and I did apologize…”<br>
“Aye, and…” cooling, “well, I apologize for going too far as well…I’m merely unsure of your motives for engaging in such a display,” Firinn said, his eyes searching her face for any hint of deception.  <br>
She looked shocked. “You…just apologized to me, didn’t you?”  She smiled broadly.<br>
“Aye, lass, I did.  You worry me, Ivri.  Most paladins fault in being over zealous in their righteousness.  You do not.  However… your language, and occasionally brutish behavior lends not to your profession.  Paladins should be pure, but not pretentious…” muses momentarily, “we seem to have some that think too highly of themselves.  That isn’t you, but you don’t seem pure either, and it cautions me, as to what you may be fighting in the dark half of your heart.”  <br>
Ivri raised her eyebrow…she didn’t think she had ever heard so much at one time from the shaman.  He must have been worrying over this for some time to be that eloquent.<br>
“Nothing that slays other beings can be pure, Firinn, I kill for a living, how can I not be brutish at times?” she sighed, falling back into the chair across from him.<br>
He looked upon her with wary eyes.  “It is not the act of killing, lass, it is what is in your heart when you swing the slaying blow… and watch the life ebb from your foe.”<br>
<br>
Ivri sighed as she stuffed the blanket into her backpack.  She had gone on to admit to Firinn that hatred was what was in her heart when she killed.  She hated her parents who made her this way, the innkeeper and his family, and all those who had ever shunned her.  It was not that way before, she used to be the most honorable paladin, kind and gentle, her trainer told her she would do great things in Karana’s name…that people could not possibly deny the goodness in her, that her parentage would not be an issue once they knew her.  Sadly, she was wrong.  It had mattered, and now she was bitter and frightened.  Frightened of herself, frightened of the way she killed, without mercy.  She had justified herself in the past by only killing that which was evil…in her heart, she knew someday that distinction would no longer matter.  Her temper was already way too short.  Of course, she had not told Firinn ALL of that…she was not stupid.  He had said that she was inadvertently serving the god of Hate, and that it would be wise for her to seek out a healer, or guidance from an elder paladin.  Someone more understanding.  Then…he reached out and pulled her into a gentle hug.  She was still shocked from THAT one.  He told her she had a home with the Elven Elite, and he was merely trying to do what was best for his home.  She broke down into tears…it had been SO embarrassing!  “I wish I had merely kept my big mouth shut!” she had said morosely, shaking her head.  “I would have found it out anyway,” Firinn replied.  She couldn’t see his face (her view restricted by massive barbarian biceps), but she could hear the smirk in his voice.  She poked him in the chest.  “You think yourself so wise!”<br>
“Humph!” he growled.  She ran to her room and started packing.  He shouted after her, “What in the world are you doing, lass?”  <br>
“I am taking your advice, Firinn.  I am going to Qeynos, to see my trainer,” she poked her head around the corner.  “Don’t mention it to anyone, please, especially Naminu…just tell them I went on a little vacation.  I don’t want them to worry.”  <br>
He nodded, albeit reluctantly.  <br>
As she ran out the door, she called over her shoulder, “thank you, Bear!”  <br>
“Good luck, lass,” he whispered.<br>
<br>
Ivri stood on a small hill, looking out over land she hadn’t seen in years.  A thunderstorm was breaking in the direction of Qeynos…and, being a worshipper of the Rainkeeper, she took it as a good omen.  “No time like the present, Iv-girl,” she muttered to herself, and set off across the plains. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#BA9F70><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=giltav>Giltav</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(11/26/02 1:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=79.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Journey &quot;Home&quot;</span><hr size=1> Giltaav watched Ivri from a nearby tree, he had been following her since he noticed her packing for a long journey, wondering where she was going.  Tracking her had not been a difficult task, she took no measures to disguise her tracks, or even hide herself from view, which was one reason he decided to keep an eye on her, the plains of Karana held few dangers for one of her skill, but there were creatures that might decide to try for a half-elf snack.  Using his magic to hide himself from her view he had followed her from the guildhall and now waited patiently for her to continue her journey.  He didn't know where her final destination was, but by all signs she was heading to her home town of Qeynos, but why?<br>
<br>
Eye's and ears accustomed to the sounds of nature, he noticed a slight shift in the early morning shadows off the north and decided to investigate while Ivri stirred and made ready to leave.  Not seeing anything to the naked eye, he quickly murmured an incantation to allow him to see that which was hidden from sight.  A dark image appeared in the rocks, still almost hidden from even his enhanced vision.  Sneaking silently closer and still using natures camoflauge he ventured closer to see what this shadowy figure was.  As he neared, the faint scent of cologne, alcohol, and perfume wafted by.  &quot;I know that smell&quot; he thought, and smiled to himself, it must be that rogue Wilwen, &quot;I wonder what business he has in these parts&quot;.<br>
<br>
Noticing that the rogue seemed to be preparing to make camp for the day and travel by night, Giltaav left and returned to keep an eye on Ivri, but she had already broken camp and moved out.  &quot;Oh well&quot; he thought and quickly checked the area for Ivri's footprints.  Finding them easily, he followed them to the west, his assumption on Ivri's destination had so far proven correct.  Deciding to keep an eye on both Wilwen and Ivri's movement made this adventure much more challenging, as the rogue was attempting to keep his movements hidden, and would be much more difficult to keep track of, a fine way to practice and hone his tracking skills.  &quot;Ah, fun fun&quot; he thought, and continued keeping a watchfull eye on the young Paladin. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#F5F5DC>- </font><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite>Elven Elite</a><font color=#F5F5DC> - </font><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5>/Roleplay</a> <font color=#F5F5DC> - </font><a href="http://www.elvenelite.com">Elven Elite Home Page</a><font color=#F5F5DC> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.245d<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

